Exercise 3 - Visualizing Data & Identifying Distributions

Learning Objectives

  • Know what data types are meant for each graph
    • 1 numeric = histogram
    • 1 numeric, 1 factor = boxplot
    • 2 numeric = scatterplot
  • Know how to improve graphs with informative labels
    • using labs() & ggtitle() functions
  • Learn tricks to making more visually appealing graphs
    • alpha for transparency
    • fill to distinguish groups
    • theme_*() to change background
      • theme_bw()
      • theme_light()
      • theme_classic()
    • theme() to change text (axis titles & texts), rectangle (facet_wrap), and legend features
      • theme(axis.text = element_text())
      • theme(strip.background = element_rect())
      • theme(legend.position = bottom)
  • Identify data distribution types

Background

You can spend hours making pretty plots in R. When you are publishing papers you may want to do just that. In this class, we are not going to worry about publication quality figures, but we are going to learn how to make figures that tell you and anyone exactly what the data are showing. This tutorial will show you some examples of making figures in R. There is no way a tutorial can tell you everything you need to know about plotting in R, so we are just going to cover the basics. I would recommend playing around with some of the code as you work through this tutorial.

Also, if you have a question about how to make certain plots check out The R gallery websites. Websites like these give you examples of how to make plots in R with all of the code included! If you get really excited about plotting in R, check out the package ggplot2. This package offers lots of options for customizing graphs and figures - see the ggplot 2 Cheat Sheet. The basic format of code in ggplot is always the same: we start by using the ggplot function to specify what data to use, and which variable to put on which axis. Then, we add on a geom using the plus sign to specify what kind of plot we want. There are a ton of other functions that can be added from there to customize the plot.

Note: You will see two ways to pass data through the ggplot() function.

  • nest data into the ggplot() function = ggplot(data,)
  • or pipe data into ggplot() function = data %>% ggplot(aes())

I prefer piping data into ggplot() because it allows for better data manipulation without altering the data set. Some helpful ways to manipulate data prior to piping into ggplot involve filter() to a specific subgroup(s) or mutate() to create numeric summaries for groups. However, either nesting or piping data in ggplot works.

Exercise 0: Layers of a ggplot

We will be exploring the data set knz_bison. This data looks at Bison (Bison bison) herd information at the Konza Prairie Biological Station LTER, which is part of The National Science Foundations (NSF) Long Term Ecological Research (LTER) program. More details about specific columns can be found on the ltersampler website.

Some questions we can answer with the following code:

  • Of the 3 plots, which plot begins to actually show the relationship between bison weight and year of birth? What functions/layers make that plot visually better?
ggplot1 <- ggplot() # plot A

ggplot2 <- ggplot(knz_bison, aes(x = animal_weight, y = animal_yob)) # plot B

ggplot3 <- ggplot(knz_bison, aes(x = animal_weight, y = animal_yob)) + # plot C
  geom_point()

plot_grid(ggplot1, ggplot2, ggplot3, # call all plots
          ncol = 3, # put plots in 3 columns
          labels = "AUTO") # add labels to plots # plot C is best plot because it has labels and data. The layers necessary to make plot c is ggplot() + aes(data) + geom_point()

Exercise 1: Histogram

A histogram is a graphical representation of the distribution of a numeric variable. The variable is cut into several bins, and the number of observations per bin is represented by the height (i.e.frequency).

Some questions we can answer with the following code:

  • Based on the histogram, what is the distribution of animal_weight for all bison? (i.e.is it symmetrical/normally distributed?)
hist <- knz_bison %>% # call in data set and then, 
  ggplot(aes(x = animal_weight)) + # with the animal weight data 
  geom_histogram(color = "#e9ecef", fill = "#69b3a2", position = "identity") + # create a histogram with color and fill 
  theme_light() + # change the background to light theme
  labs(x = "Bison Weight (k)", y = "Frequency") + # create unique labels
  ggtitle("Untransformed Weight of all Bison") + # give plot a title
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold")) # The distribution of all bison looks slightly right skewed.

hist

  • Based on the histograms, does a log or square root transformation of animal_weight improve the normal distribution?
# note: because the previous histogram shows there are no bison with weight = 0 k, 
# I do not have to add +1 to the log transformation

log_hist <- knz_bison %>%  # call in data set and then, 
  mutate(log_weight = log(animal_weight)) %>%  # create a new column called `log_weight` with the log of animal weight
  ggplot(aes(x = log_weight)) + # with the LOG of animal weight data
  geom_histogram(color = "#e9ecef", fill = "#69b3a2", position = "identity") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Log of Bison Weight (k)", y = "Frequency") + # NOTE: I add LOG of Bison Weight bc that is what I'm displaying
  ggtitle("Log Weight of all Bison") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold")) # The distribution of all bison looks slightly left skewed.


sqrt_hist <- knz_bison %>%  # call in data set and then, 
  mutate(sqrt_weight = sqrt(animal_weight)) %>%  # create a new column called `log_weight` with the log of animal weight
  ggplot(aes(x = sqrt_weight)) + # with the SQRT of animal weight data
  geom_histogram(color = "#e9ecef", fill = "#69b3a2", position = "identity") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Square-root of Bison Weight (k)", y = "Frequency") + # NOTE: I add SQRT of Bison Weight bc that is what I'm displaying
  ggtitle("Square-root Weight of all Bison") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold")) # The sqrt transformation made the weight distribution looks the closest to normal, but still not great

# cowplot package has the function `plot_grid` which makes multi-plot figures look nice
plot_grid(hist,log_hist, sqrt_hist, # call the 3 histograms we made
          ncol = 1, # put all 3 hist in 1 column
          align = "v", # align all 3 hist vertically
          labels = "AUTO", # add the auto label A, B, C
          label_size = 11) # make label font size 11

  • Based on the histogram, does the distribution of animal_weight look similar for each animal_sex (i.e.Female or Male)?
knz_bison %>% 
  plyr::mutate(animal_sex = revalue(animal_sex, c("F"= "Female", "M" = "Male"))) %>% # in plyr package, mutate values in animal sex column to spell out Female and Male
  ggplot(aes(x = animal_weight, fill = animal_sex)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "grey10",  position = "identity", alpha = .7) + # alpha increases transparency so you can see both groups
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#3d405b", "#81b29a")) + # manually supply 2 colors to 2 groups
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Bison Weight (k)", y = "Frequency", fill = "Sex") +
  ggtitle("Histogram") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = "bottom") # distribution for female and male look different with females more left skew and males more right skew

Exercise 2: Boxplot

Another way we can visualize the distribution of weight (numeric) by bison sex (factor) is with a boxplot. A boxplot visually represents the numeric distribution by factor/grouping. data-to-vis describes the elements of a box plots:

  • The line that divides the box into 2 parts represents the median of the data. If the median is 10, it means that there are the same number of data points below and above 10

  • The ends of the box shows the upper (Q3) and lower (Q1) quartiles. If the third quartile is 15, it means that 75% of the observation are lower than 15

  • The difference between Quartiles 1 and 3 is called the interquartile range (IQR)

  • The extreme line shows Q3+1.5xIQR to Q1-1.5xIQR (the highest and lowest value excluding outliers)

  • Dots (or other markers) beyond the extreme line shows potential outliers

Some questions we can answer with the following code:

  • Based on the boxplot, how do the medians and dispersions compare between female and male bison?
  • Based on the boxplot, do you see outliers?
knz_bison %>% 
  plyr::mutate(animal_sex = revalue(animal_sex, c("F"= "Female", "M" = "Male"))) %>% # in plyr package, mutate values in animal sex column to spell out Female and Male
  ggplot(aes(x = animal_sex, y = animal_weight, fill = animal_sex)) +
  geom_jitter(alpha = .02, fill = "grey90")+ # add points behind geom_boxplot to get a better idea of the distribution of weight
  geom_boxplot(alpha = .9) + # increase the transparency of the boxplot to see points behind them
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#3d405b", "#81b29a")) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Bison Sex", y = "Bison Weight (k)", fill = "Sex") +
  ggtitle("Histogram") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = "bottom") # The medians are not the same, with females on average having higher median value for weight (k) # The dispersion are not the same, with males on average having more variation (i.e. larger boxplot) # yes, males have individual bison outliers that are larger than the average male bison

Exercise 3: Scatterplot

We will be exploring the data set vertebrates. This data looks at Cutthroat trout (Oncorhynchus clarkii) and salamander (family Salamandridae) length and weights in Mack Creek, Andrews Forest LTER, which is part of The National Science Foundations (NSF) Long Term Ecological Research (LTER) program. More details about specific columns can be found on the ltersampler website.

A scatterplot displays the relationship between two numeric variables where each dot represents an observation.

Some questions we can answer with the following code:

  • Based on the scatterplot, how what is the trend between vertebrate length and mass? Is the trending relationship similar for both species?
vertebrates %>% 
  filter(species == "Cutthroat trout" | species == "Coastal giant salamander")  %>% # filtered to 2 most common species
  ggplot(aes(x = length_1_mm, y = weight_g)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species),alpha = .7) + # color the points by species
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#e36414", "#0f4c5c")) + # want to use these 2 specific colors for 2 species
  theme_classic() + # changed background
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + # added the trend line using a linear model (lm) method
  labs(x = "Vertebrate Length (mm)", y = "Vertebrate Mass (g)", color = "Species") +
  ggtitle("Scatterplot") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = c(.15,.87), # put the legend in a specific location on the plot
        legend.key = element_rect(color = "transparent", fill = "transparent")) # The relationship between length and mass is trending positively, meaning for every 1 unit increase in length there is an increase in mass, however it is not a 1:1 relationship or else that would be a perfect 45 degree line. Although there are some outliers for both species, it seems like there is a positive trend for both species.

  • How does the 2nd scatterplot differ from the 1st scatterplot?
vertebrates %>% 
  filter(species == "Cutthroat trout" | species == "Coastal giant salamander")  %>% # filtered to 2 most common species
  ggplot(aes(x = length_1_mm, y = weight_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .7) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#e36414", "#0f4c5c")) + # want to use these 2 specific colors for 2 species
  theme_classic() + # changed background
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + # added the trend line using a linear model (lm) method
  labs(x = "Vertebrate Length (mm)", y = "Vertebrate Mass (g)", color = "Species") +
  ggtitle("Scatterplot") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = c(.15,.87)) # in the 2nd scatterplot, there is only 1 trend line for both species, instead of 2 trend lines for each species, which is controled by the `color = species` in ggplot() function. Also, the legend box is transparent in the 1st graph because of the legend.key argument in the theme() function.

Exercise 4: Facet Wrap

What if you wanted to explore a numeric trend, but think site location (or another categorical context) may influence the numeric x-y relationship you see? Facet Wrap is a great layer to provide context to your numeric relationship, especially if you think some numeric relationships may be influenced by site or species characteristics.

Some questions we can answer with the following code:

  • Based on this facet wrap scatterplot, which site has the most outliers?
vertebrates %>% 
  filter(species != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = length_1_mm, y = weight_g)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = species)) +
  facet_wrap(~sitecode) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Vertebrate Length (mm)", y = "Vertebrate Mass (g)", color = "Species") +
  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(size = 12),
        legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        legend.position = "bottom",
        strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey25"),
        strip.text = element_text(face = "bold", size = 12))  # Both MACKOG-U and MACKOG-M have several outliers

  • What is the difference between strip.background and strip.text?

    • With strip.background, you can change the color of the facet wrap using the element_rect() function.
    • With strip.text you can change the text of the facet wrap using the element_text() function.

Exercise 5: Identify distributions

In lecture, you will hear a lot about data distributions. Data distributions are important to know because how your data is distributed ( central tendency (i.e.mean) and spread (i.e.variance)) will determine which statistical tests you can accurately run. This is a brief section with simulated data to show you what some important data distributions look like.

# Normal distribution -- good for parametric statistical tests
rand_norms_1000 <- rnorm(n = 1000, mean = 0, sd = 1) # simulate 1000 data observations that follows normal distribution (i.e. rnorm()) with mean = 0, sd = 1
hist(rand_norms_1000, # plot a histogram of data in base R
     xlab = "Random value (X)", main = "Normal Distribution", # change labels
     col = "grey",cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.5) # add stylistic flair

# Poisson distribution -- (mostly) not good for parametric statistical tests
rand_poissons_1000 <- rpois(n = 1000, lambda = 4.5) # simulate 1000 data that follows poisson distribution (i.e. rpois()) with lambda = 4.5 
hist(rand_poissons_1000, # plot a histogram of data in base R
     xlab = "Random value (X)", main = "Poisson Distribution", # change labels
     col = "grey", cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.5) # add stylistic flair

# Uniform distribution -- not good for parametric statistical tests
rand_unifs_1000 <- runif(n = 1000, min = 0, max = 1) # simulate 1000 data that follows uniform distribution (i.e. runif()) bounded by 0-1 
hist(rand_unifs_1000, # plot a histogram of data in base R
     xlab = "Random value (X)", main = "Uniform Distribution", # change labels
     col = "grey", cex.lab = 1.5, cex.axis = 1.5) # add stylistic flair

Vocab

In this Exercise and much of EEMB146, plotting will be done in ggplot. But base R still works and can be great for plotting. Below, I go over the basics functions for plotting in base R. By using the ? in R you can figure out the details of these different plotting functions.

  1. plot() : Plot x and y against each other
  2. hist() : Make a histogram of your data
  3. scatterplot() : Make a scatter plot of x and y
  4. abline() : Add a straight line to your current plot
  5. lines() : Add more lines/data to your current plot
  6. curve() : Plot a function over some range
  7. boxplot() : Make a box plot to compare different groups of your data 8. densityPlot() : Fit a density kernel to your data
  8. pie() : Make a pie chart
  9. barplot() : Make a bar graph in R 11. mosaicplot() : Make a mosaic plot
